The Yoneda Lemma is perhaps the most famous result in category theory.
One way of interpreting it is to say that you can reconstruct,
up to isomorphism, an object in a category from its web of connections
with other objects in that category.

Category theory being the favorite pasttime of smart nerds
afraid to get their hands dirty with the real work of mathematics
(I should know, this describes me more often than note),
it's easy to dismiss this observation as clever abstract nonsense,
but there's really quite a lot of mileage you can get out of it.
[Emily Riehl][Riehl] gives a great example in her excellent book [Category Theory In Context][Cat],
using the "universal property" (see below) of the tensor product of two vector spaces
to sketch how one might come up with the usual construction with "formal" tensors.

As a group theorist interested more and more in topological groups,
I'd like to attempt to do the same thing for free constructions on groups and topological groups.

